President Biden hosted a virtual meeting with the leaders of the Quad group, which consists of the United States, Australia, India, and Japan. The Quad was established in 2007 in response to the 2004 tsunami, and this is the first time the group is meeting at a leader level. President Biden emphasized the importance of a free and open Indo-Pacific region and expressed the United States' commitment to working with its partners and allies to achieve stability. He highlighted the impact of the recently signed American Rescue Plan on the U.S. economy and global growth. The Quad leaders discussed various topics, including vaccines, climate change, and emerging technologies, and expressed their commitment to promoting a secure, stable, and prosperous Indo-Pacific. Prime Minister Morrison of Australia, Prime Minister Modi of India, and Prime Minister Suga of Japan also shared their remarks during the meeting.